Overview

A Discreet EEG-tDCS Headband for Real-Time Detection and Modulation of

Anxiety-Related Brain Activity

Overview

This design document proposes a discreet and wearable headband-system that integrates

both EEG and tDCS to detect and modulate neural activities that can be associated with anxiety.

The device consists of flexible electrodes sewn into the headband, allowing for continuous EEG

monitoring and user-initiated neuromodulation through tDCS. Paired with a mobile app, the

system identifies anxiety-related neural patterns and notifies the user when these patterns appear.

If the user chooses to engage, they can initiate a session of tDCS through the mobile app, which

also receives data from the device and stores long-term trends.

By combining EEG detection with user-activated tDCS in a single system, the design

provides a closed-loop approach for supporting anxiety regulation in everyday contexts. It is

grounded in established evidence on EEG biomarkers of anxiety and dorsolateral prefrontal

cortex (DLPFC) tDCS effects on emotional regulation.

EEG Biomarkers of Anxiety

Anxiety is closely tied to patterns in neural activity that can be measured through EEG.

Three types of EEG markers are relevant for detecting both momentary anxiety responses and

stable, trait anxiety tendencies: frontal alpha asymmetry, high-beta activity and theta-beta ratios,

and atypical resting-state rhythmic activities. Together, these biomarkers can identify

anxiety-related states in real time through a wearable EEG device.

Frontal alpha asymmetry (FAA) reflects an imbalance of activity between the left and

right frontal regions, and is typically calculated by subtracting alpha power in left frontal

electrodes from the alpha power in the right frontal electrodes. The left frontal cortex is

associated with approach-related motivation and engagement, while the right frontal cortex is

associated with withdrawal-related behaviors, negative affect, and a heightened sensitivity to

threat. Because alpha power is inversely related to cortical activity, a negative FAA value

indicates lower alpha power in the right frontal cortex relative to the left, reflecting greater right

---

frontal cortex activity, which is a pattern consistent with negative affect and anxiety-related

emotional processing (Barros et al., 2022). This makes FAA a reliable metric for detecting both

momentary and trait-like anxiety tendencies.

Beta waves reflect cortical arousal and attentional engagement, increasing when the brain

is in a state of heightened vigilance. Among beta ranges, high-beta activity (25-30 Hz) is most

strongly associated with fear, hyperarousal, and anxiety. Increased high-beta activity is a

characteristic pattern in individuals with anxiety disorders and reflects elevated activity in

cortical networks involved in threat monitoring. An increased theta-beta ratio (TBR) suggests

that the thalamus-cortex interaction is disrupted, which is correlated with trait anxiety and

difficulties with attentional control (Byeon et al., 2023). Taken together, elevations in beta power

and increased theta-beta ratios indicate anxious arousal that can be reliably monitored in real

time through a wearable EEG system.

Resting-state rhythmic activity also provides insight into stable patterns of anxiety. When

individuals are not engaged in a task, internal processes like rumination, hypervigilance, and

anticipatory worry influence rhythmic brain activity in individuals with higher trait anxiety and

neuroticism. Focusing on rhythmic oscillations in the alpha and beta ranges can reveal tendencies

linked to an overactive behavioral inhibition system, which promotes caution, avoidance, and

increased threat monitoring (Shalamberidze et al., 2025). Resting-state rhythms reflect the

brain‚Äôs intrinsic emotional and cognitive tendencies independent of external task demands,

making them an important complement to FAA and beta-based markers when identifying

anxious tendencies.

FAA, high-beta activity, and increased theta-beta ratios capture immediate fluctuations in

anxious arousal, while resting-state rhythms reveal long-term vulnerabilities to anxious

tendencies. Integrating these biomarkers enables the proposed system to monitor both real-time

anxiety spikes and intrinsic predispositions toward heightened worry, which supports

personalized responsive anxiety-regulation interventions.

EEG Electrodes & Placements

The proposed system is designed as a sport-style headband that can be worn comfortably

during daily life while still detecting and modulating anxiety-related brain activity.

Garment-EEG sensors are light, soft, and bendable, created by combining conductive and

isolating fibers. This construction allows the electrodes to conform comfortably to the scalp

without bulky hardware while still producing recordings comparable to dry-EEG systems,

though with greater susceptibility to artifacts (L√≥pez-Larraz et al., 2023). The headband contains

four surface electrodes positioned over frontal and parietal regions that lie naturally under a

headband.

Sensors placed at F3 and F4, over the left and right frontal lobes, are used to measure

frontal alpha asymmetry (FAA). Because FAA reflects the balance between approach and

withdrawal emotional tendencies, placing electrodes at these sites allows the device to measure

these biomarkers in real time.

---

The Fz electrode sits at the frontal midline, a region involved in vigilance, cognitive

tension, and effortful attention regulation. Elevated high-beta activity and increased theta-beta

ratios at this site are biomarkers of anxious arousal and reflect disruptions in the top-down

attentional control network associated with the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (Putman et al.,

2014).

To incorporate information about resting-state rhythmic activities that reflect more stable

tendencies toward trait anxiety, the device also includes a posterior electrode at POz. Alpha and

beta rhythms are reliably detected at parietal locations and are associated with fluctuations in

arousal, internal attention, and cognitive states like rumination or hypervigilance (Shalamberidze

et al., 2025). Monitoring POz allows the device to differentiate between immediate anxiety

spikes detected at the frontal sites and the user‚Äôs baseline rhythmic activity.

tDCS Electrodes & Placements

The headband incorporates a pair of tDCS electrodes sewn into the headband‚Äôs fabric to

ensure stable contact and current distribution during daily wear. To stimulate the left DLPFC, the

anode is positioned at F3, and the cathode is placed at the bottom of the headband over the contra

lateral supraorbital area (Vanderhasselt et al., 2013). This formation is supported in

neuromodulation research, as anodal stimulation of the left DLPFC has been shown to reduce

biased attention to threat, reduce negative emotional reactivity in the amygdala, and improve

cognitive control over affective material (Clarke et al., 2020).

The tDCS component provides low-intensity neuromodulation that can be initiated by the

user when the device detects elevated anxiety-related EEG patterns. The left DLPFC is an

effective target for this, as anxiety-related disorders are associated with frontal alpha asymmetry,

hypoactivity in the left DLPFC and hyperactivity in the right. Neuromodulation techniques, like

tDCS, influence the activity of these networks by increasing excitability under the anode placed

over the left DLPFC. Studies using prefrontal tDCS report reductions in anxiety symptoms

across anxiety-related conditions and demonstrate improvements in emotional regulation and

attentional control (Stein et al., 2020).

Signal Processing & Data Analysis

To conserve battery power and keep the device lightweight, the headband only performs

tasks like signal acquisition, amplification, digitization, and wireless transmission to the paired

mobile app. Once EEG signals are collected from the headband, the device sends the raw data to

the mobile app via Bluetooth.

The mobile app receives the raw EEG data stream and conducts all real-time signal

processing. It applies filtering and artifact-reduction algorithms to remove environmental noise,

muscle activity, and motion artifacts. The cleaned EEG signal is then segmented into short time

windows that serve as the basis for real-time feature extraction. Within each window, the app

calculates any anxiety-related EEG biomarkers found throughout the system.

The mobile app also establishes and maintains individualized thresholds derived from

each user‚Äôs baseline activity. During initial setup, the app records several minutes of resting-state

EEG to determine the user‚Äôs typical alpha, beta, and theta levels. These personalized values are

---

set as reference points for the system to detect any meaningful deviations that could be

associated with anxious arousal.

When the mobile app detects that any extracted features exceed the user‚Äôs baseline

thresholds, it sends the user a notification indicating that anxiety-related neural patterns are

elevated. If the user chooses to engage, they can initiate a tDCS session through the mobile app,

which sends the command back to the headband.

Safety Analysis

The device follows established safety guidelines for low-intensity transcranial electrical

stimulation and wearable EEG. For tDCS, the device delivers 1-2 mA of direct current with a

maximum of 60 minutes of total daily stimulation, parameters that fall within the safety range.

These dosing limits ensure that stimulation remains within safe boundaries and reduce the risk of

excessive current exposure or neuroplastic effects associated with prolonged, high-current

stimulation. To support flexible and personalized use while maintaining safe parameters, the

system supports up to four 15-minute user-activated sessions per day, each including gradual

ramp-up and ramp-down periods to prevent abrupt onset and offset stimulation and minimize

discomfort, complying with recommended stimulation practices (Antal et al., 2017).

The device uses current-controlled stimulation circuitry that maintains stable current

delivery within the recommended 1-2 mA range (Antal et al., 2017). If the headband detects

inadequate electrode contact, it automatically pauses the session to maintain safe and consistent

stimulation conditions.

The EEG component of the device is passive and non-invasive, relying on surface

electrodes that record scalp potentials. Garment-EEG electrodes have been demonstrated to be

safe for extended wear, provided that contact pressure is comfortable and materials are

breathable (L√≥pez-Larraz et al., 2023). The headband design avoids the use of adhesives or gels

and reduces the risk of skin irritation.

Conclusion

This design document proposes a discreet, wearable system that integrates EEG

monitoring with user-activated tDCS to support the regulation of anxiety-related neural activity

in everyday settings. By combining garment-based electrodes, establishing biomarkers of

anxious arousal, flexible tDCS targeting of the left DLPFC, and app-based signal processing, the

design offers a closed-loop approach that is both lightweight and grounded in current evidence.

The system provides users with real-time insight into their own neural patterns and a

neuromodulation tool that may help in reducing elevated activity when it happens. While

empirical testing would be required to validate the design‚Äôs effectiveness, the device is a feasible

application of existing neurotechnology. It demonstrates how wearable EEG and non-invasive

stimulation can be integrated into an everyday system to support emotional well-being in a

personalized way.
